   =20
 =20
A dumb simple model of artificial intelligence companies is:=09It would be =
good to develop good AI (AI that helps humans), but bad to develop bad AI (=
AI that kills or enslaves humans).=09If you try to build good AI, there is =
some risk of building bad AI instead (your robot tricks you into thinking t=
hat it=E2=80=99s nice, then enslaves you), so you have to be very very care=
ful. You can=E2=80=99t move too fast; you have to check carefully, at each =
step, to make sure that your robot is not secretly evil.=09Company A is for=
med by idealistic AI researchers who want to create good AI. They work toge=
ther well for a while.=09Disagreements develop. Some researchers at Company=
 A say =E2=80=9Cwe need to work faster to build good AI, because if we don=
=E2=80=99t, someone else will come along and build bad AI first instead.=E2=
=80=9D Others say =E2=80=9Cno, we can=E2=80=99t work faster, that would com=
promise our ability to check that the robot is not evil.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=09T=
he first group wins the argument, for reasons.
  [5]
=09The people who lose the argument, who are genuinely worried about bad AI=
, quit Company A=C2=A0in outrage and go start Company B, with the goal of c=
arefully and safely creating good AI.=09They work together well for a few m=
onths.=09Disagreements develop at Company B. Some researchers say =E2=80=9C=
we need to work faster to build good AI, because otherwise=C2=A0Company A w=
ill build bad AI first. That=E2=80=99s why we quit, after all.=E2=80=9D Oth=
ers say =E2=80=9Cno, we can=E2=80=99t work faster, that would compromise ou=
r bad robot checks.=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s=C2=A0why we quit, after all.=E2=80=
=9D=09The first group wins the argument, for the same reasons as in Step 5.=
=09The people who lose the argument quit and start Company C.=09This keeps =
repeating: Company C eventually splits over similar tensions, but also Comp=
any A and Company B can themselves keep dividing as some people want to mov=
e faster than others.=09Eventually all the AI researchers are very finely s=
orted by aggressiveness, so that Company Z is full of purists who are too c=
autious ever to build anything at all, while Company A is full of people wh=
o are like =E2=80=9Cactually being enslaved by robots would be pretty cool.=
=E2=80=9DThis is not accurate in all respects =E2=80=94=C2=A0sometimes the =
second group wins the argument for a weekend! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is an i=
ntuitive model that helps to explain stuff like this:For the past several m=
onths, the question =E2=80=9CWhere=E2=80=99s Ilya?=E2=80=9D has become a co=
mmon refrain within the world of artificial intelligence. Ilya Sutskever, t=
he famed researcher who co-founded OpenAI, took part in the 2023 board oust=
er of Sam Altman as chief executive officer, before changing course and hel=
ping engineer Altman=E2=80=99s return. From that point on, Sutskever went q=
uiet and left his future at OpenAI shrouded in uncertainty. Then, in mid-Ma=
y, Sutskever announced his departure, saying only that he=E2=80=99d disclos=
e his next project =E2=80=9Cin due time.=E2=80=9DNow Sutskever is introduci=
ng that project, a venture called Safe Superintelligence Inc. aiming to cre=
ate a safe, powerful artificial intelligence system within a pure research =
organization that has no near-term intention of selling AI products or serv=
ices. In other words, he=E2=80=99s attempting to continue his work without =
many of the distractions that rivals such as OpenAI, Google and Anthropic f=
ace. =E2=80=9CThis company is special in that its first product will be the=
 safe superintelligence, and it will not do anything else up until then,=E2=
=80=9D Sutskever says in an exclusive interview about his plans. =E2=80=9CI=
t will be fully insulated from the outside pressures of having to deal with=
 a large and complicated product and having to be stuck in a competitive ra=
t race.=E2=80=9DOpenAI was founded to build artificial general intelligence=
 safely, free of outside commercial pressures. And now every once in a whil=
e it shoots out a new AI firm whose mission is to build artificial general =
intelligence safely, free of the commercial pressures at OpenAI.
