or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">running a family office</a>.=E2=80=9D Also he sent Virgin =E2=80=9Ca =
screenshot of a bank account in the name of Matthew Brown Companies,=E2=80=
=9D showing a balance of $182 million. But the screenshot was allegedly fab=
ricated, and the actual balance =E2=80=9Cwas less than $1.=E2=80=9D</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two wild things here. First: It totally worked! Br=
own got exactly what anyone who has ever wanted to do a fake takeover offer=
 would hope for: a termsheet and a CNBC appearance. The termsheet:</p><bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By falsely portraying his experience an=
d available funding, Brown was able to engage Virgin Orbit in negotiations =
over his bogus offer. At the outset of these negotiations, Virgin Orbit sen=
t Brown a non-disclosure agreement (=E2=80=9CNDA=E2=80=9D) requiring each s=
ide to safeguard and not disclose any confidential information exchanged du=
ring discussions surrounding Defendants=E2=80=99 proposed investment. Both =
sides executed the NDA on or around March 19 or 20, 2023. At Defendants=E2=
=80=99 request, Virgin Orbit also prepared and sent Defendants a term sheet=
 for the proposed $200 million investment on or around March 20, 2023. The =
term sheet provided for Brown to receive $200 million of Virgin Orbit prefe=
rred stock, convertible to common stock following stockholder and regulator=
y approval, in exchange for Brown=E2=80=99s $200 million investment. =E2=80=
=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Brown also sought to induce Virgin Orbi=
t to expedite the transaction. For example, on March 20, 2023, after Virgin=
 Orbit sent Brown and his lawyer a draft term sheet, Brown responded: =E2=
=80=9C[i]n the interest of time, let us both work together outside counsel =
until definitive=C2=A0agreements. (aka let us get the [term sheet] executed=
 and then we can run the race =E2=80=93 I would prefer to do the [term shee=
t] tonight or within the next 24hr.).=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">I feel like he is not using the phrase =E2=80=9Coutside co=
unsel=E2=80=9D there in exactly the way an experienced deal person would us=
e it, but never mind.=C2=A0The CNBC appearance<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Despite having executed a=
n NDA with Virgin Orbit only days earlier, Brown appeared on CNBC on March =
23, 2023, where he participated in a live, nationally televised interview t=
hat was broadcast to the general public. During that interview, Brown confi=
rmed the reported $200 million investment offer that he and his company pro=
posed to Virgin Orbit. Brown further represented that he and his company we=
re in =E2=80=9Cfinal discussions=E2=80=9D with Virgin Orbit and that they =
=E2=80=9Cfully plan=E2=80=9D on closing a transaction =E2=80=9Cin the next =
24 hours.=E2=80=9D Although he suggested that he=C2=A0could not get into th=
e details of the discussions, he confirmed his proposed investment would =
=E2=80=9Cmake [Virgin Orbit] cash flow positive=E2=80=9D and that he would =
=E2=80=9Cbasically be the owner=E2=80=9D of Virgin Orbit as a result of the=
 transaction.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During his CNBC interview, Br=
own also portrayed himself and Matthew Brown Companies as successful, exper=
ienced venture capitalists within the space industry. He even claimed that =
he and his company held investments =E2=80=9Cin over 13 space companies.=E2=
=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In reality, Brown and his company ha=
d never held any investments or positions in any space companies, much less=
 investments in =E2=80=9Cover 13 space companies.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That really is the dream: You send a fak=
e merger offer to a public company, the public company enters into serious =
negotiations with you, you go on TV (in violation of your real NDA!) to dis=
cuss your fake takeover, you get to live the life of a Big-Shot Deal Guy fo=
r a week.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other wild thing is: The SEC =
does not even allege that he traded the stock.<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> On March 22 =E2=80=94=C2=A0a few days after his first contact, and the=
 day before his TV hit =E2=80=94=C2=A0Reuters reported that Virgin Orbit wa=
s working on a fundraising deal with him, and the stock went up 33% on the =
day. So there was a profitable trade to be done, but he didn=E2=80=99t do i=
t.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC alleges that he did try to get s=
ome money out of it, but in a weird way:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Shortly after the CNBC interview, Brown attempted=E2=80=94unsucce=
ssfully=E2=80=94to profit from his deceptive conduct (and his false and mis=
leading statements and omissions) through a proposed =E2=80=9Cbreak-up=E2=
=80=9D fee. Specifically, on March 24, 2023, Brown wrote to Virgin Orbit, l=
amenting that he =E2=80=9Cwish[ed] [his] name was never made public,=E2=80=
=9D and that he had supposedly =E2=80=9Cbeen on the=C2=A0phone nonstop sinc=
e the leak=E2=80=9D of his offer (i.e., the Reuters article). Thus, before =
signing a term sheet that required him to disclose confidential information=
 to Virgin Orbit, Brown proposed that=C2=A0Virgin Orbit agree to =E2=80=9Ca=
 break up fee of 3%=E2=80=9D to be paid to him if the investment transactio=
n did not close.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By this point=
 Virgin Orbit had apparently gotten the idea that he was fake, so they aske=
d him for proof of the money:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">V=
irgin Orbit refused Brown=E2=80=99s break-up fee proposal and responded on =
March 24, 2023: =E2=80=9C[i]f you have funds and can place them in a verifi=
able escrow account with the appropriate agreement and can send to us [then=
] we can discuss.=E2=80=9D Brown responded by again asking for Virgin Orbit=
 to agree to a break-up fee, to which Virgin Orbit again reiterated that Br=
own needed to first place the necessary funds in escrow and respond to Virg=
in Orbit=E2=80=99s basic due diligence requests.</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That went nowhere, the deal fizzled and Virgin Orbit f=
iled for bankruptcy in April. I suppose one possibility is that this was=C2=
=A0a form of the classic <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/35781629.259288/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvQWR2YW5jZS1m=
ZWVfc2NhbQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB66a5588c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">advance-fee scam</a>:=
 You call up a public company in desperate need of money, you say =E2=80=9C=
I can give you $200 million,=E2=80=9D they jump at the opportunity, and you=
 say =E2=80=9Cfor important reasons, I will need you to give me $6 million =
first before I can give you the $200 million.=E2=80=9D Only instead of an a=
dvance fee, it=E2=80=99s a breakup fee payable when, inevitably, your $200 =
million deal falls through. I have to say, this is kind of a rough way to m=
ake $6 million. It=E2=80=99s a public company; they=E2=80=99re not going to=
 agree to give you $6 million without some proof that you are serious. Also=
, this is a pretty=C2=A0<em>broke=C2=A0</em>public company; the chances the=
y will give you $6 million, as a breakup fee for a failed equity investment=
, as they head into bankruptcy, are pretty low.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">The other possibilities are (1) he wasn=E2=80=99t kidding,=C2=A0the pr=
oposal was real, he wanted to invest $200 million in Virgin Orbit, he had t=
he money, =E2=80=9Cthe SEC=E2=80=99s complaint is filled with egregious err=
ors,=E2=80=9D and this is all a misunderstanding, or (2) the proposal was f=
ake, but there was no serious plan to make money off of it. He just wanted =
to go on television.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" width=
